Experimental Results Analysis
Overview
This experiment implements an end-to-end IoT sensor data pipeline, covering Kafka ingestion, Spark Structured Streaming processing, multi-zone data lake storage, Spark SQL analytics, and REST API exposure. The pipeline processes 5,000 sensor events (temperature, humidity, pressure) and generates analytical results for anomaly detection, statistical analysis, and partition pruning verification. The key results are summarized and analyzed below.
1. Top 5 Hours with the Highest Anomalies (Q1)
Result (q1_top_hours.csv)
表格
h	count
10	2,862
Analysis
Dominant Anomaly Hour: The 10th hour accounts for 2,862 anomalies, which is the peak anomaly period in the dataset.
Anomaly Concentration: Over 57% of total anomalies (2,862/5,000) occur in a single hour, indicating a time-concentrated anomaly pattern (e.g., sensor malfunctions, environmental spikes, or abnormal data injection).
Business Implication: This peak hour requires priority investigation by the maintenance team to identify root causes (e.g., faulty sensors, extreme environmental changes).
2. Global Sensor Statistics & Anomaly Rates (Q2)
Result (q2_global_stats.csv)
表格
sensor	mean_val	min_val	max_val	std_dev	anomaly_rate_pct
humidity	62.25	10.03	114.91	22.41	10.86%
temperature	30.39	-4.96	64.74	11.71	36.24%
pressure	1010.06	960.20	1059.45	20.68	39.05%
Analysis
2.1 Data Distribution Characteristics
Humidity: Mean = 62.25% (normal range: 30–95%), moderate volatility (std_dev=22.41), min/max values include outliers (10.03% / 114.91%).
Temperature: Mean = 30.39°C (normal range: 15–45%), moderate volatility (std_dev=11.71), extreme outliers (-4.96°C / 64.74°C) leading to high anomalies.
Pressure: Mean = 1010.06 hPa (normal range: 980–1040%), high volatility (std_dev=20.68), extreme outliers (960.20 hPa / 1059.45 hPa).
2.2 Anomaly Rate Ranking
Pressure: 39.05% (highest, sensitive to environmental fluctuations)
Temperature: 36.24% (second, prone to extreme values)
Humidity: 10.86% (lowest, most stable sensor)
2.3 Business Insight
Pressure and temperature sensors have abnormally high anomaly rates (>35%), indicating potential hardware faults or data transmission errors.
Humidity sensors are the most reliable, with anomalies only ~10%, consistent with typical industrial IoT sensor performance.
